Name: John Smith
Age: 65
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, benign prostatic hyperplasia

Case Presentation:

John Smith is a 65-year-old retired Caucasian male who presents with complaints of difficulty with urination and lower back pain. He has a past medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. On physical examination, his prostate is enlarged and firm. A prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test is ordered and comes back elevated at 20 ng/mL.

Further imaging studies reveal a suspicious mass in the prostate gland. A biopsy is performed, and the results confirm the diagnosis of prostate cancer. The cancer is localized within the prostate gland and has not spread to other organs.

John is referred to a urologist and radiation oncologist for further management. After discussing the risks and benefits of different treatment options, John chooses to undergo radiation therapy. He receives external beam radiation to the prostate gland for a total of eight weeks, with minimal side effects.

Name: John Smith
Age: 65
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired accountant
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, type 2 diabetes

Presentation of Case:
John Smith is a 65-year-old retired accountant who presents to his primary care provider with complaints of urinary frequency and urgency, as well as difficulty initiating a stream of urine. He also reports occasional blood in his urine. On physical examination, the prostate is enlarged and nodular. A prostate-specific antigen (PSA) blood test is ordered and comes back elevated. A biopsy of the prostate is performed, which reveals adenocarcinoma. Further imaging studies show no evidence of metastatic disease. John is referred to a urologist for further management of his prostate cancer.

Name: John Doe
Age: 65
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, benign prostatic hyperplasia

Presentation:

John Doe is a 65-year-old retired Caucasian male who presents to the urology clinic with complaints of urinary hesitancy and increased frequency. He reports having these symptoms for the past 6 months but they have become progressively worse over time. He denies any pain or blood in his urine. 

Upon further evaluation, John's prostate-specific antigen (PSA) level is found to be elevated at 12 ng/mL (normal range: <4 ng/mL). A digital rectal exam (DRE) reveals a firm, nodular prostate gland. A prostate biopsy is performed, which confirms the presence of adenocarcinoma in the prostate gland. 

John's Gleason score is 7 (3+4), indicating a moderately aggressive cancer. He undergoes further imaging studies to assess the extent of the cancer, which shows no evidence of metastasis. After discussing the risks and benefits of treatment options, John opts for radical prostatectomy to remove the cancer.
